I can walk you through creating a simple "read more" button using HTML and CSS, similar to the one on the Proof Mario website. Let's take a look:

HTML:

```html
<button class="read-more">Read More</button>
```

CSS:

```css
.read-more {
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: #ffffff;
  border: none;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  font-size: 16px;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: background-color 0.2s ease-in-out;
}

.read-more:hover {
  background-color: #0056b3;
}

.read-more:after {
  content: "\25BC";
  font-size: 16px;
  margin-left: 10px;
}

.read-more:active:after {
  transform: rotate(180deg);
}
```

This code does the following:

- Styles the button with the `.read-more` class.
- Changes the button's background color on hover.
- Adds a downward arrow icon to the button's text using the `:after` pseudo-element.
- Rotates the icon on button click using the `:active` pseudo-class.

To display or hide the content when the button is clicked, you can use this JavaScript snippet:

```javascript
const readMoreButton = document.querySelector('.read-more');
const content = document.querySelector('.content');

readMoreButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
  if (content.style.display === 'block') {
    content.style.display = 'none';
    readMoreButton.textContent = 'Read More';
  } else {
    content.style.display = 'block';
    readMoreButton.textContent = 'Read Less';
  }
});
```

Here's what this JavaScript does:

- Selects the `.read-more` button and `.content` element.
- Adds a click event listener to the button.
- Toggles the content's visibility and the button's text between "Read More" and "Read Less".

